repo.description: The most widely used Python to C compiler
repo.name: cython

body:
https://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0489

Currently blocks module reloading by always returning the same module instance, but at least runs as much of the module init function on reload (or load in a subinterpreter) to configure the surroundings.

commit.message: Initial attempt at allowing to re-execute a module through PEP 489 initialisation.
Make most of the module init code re-entrant on reload by preventing to overwrite global constants.
Add a --pep489 test mode that reloads modules.
Initialise all cached/interned Python references to NULL.
First steps towards untangling implicit dependencies on static global names.
Enforce one-time initialisation of cached global Python constants (which can also be shared across subinterpreters).
Split basic PEP-489 support from reload/subinterpreter support since most modules will not trivially support re-execution.
Make reload case distinguishable in test runner.
Enforce one-time init for extension types even on reload.
Enforce one-time module code execution if "reinit" is not enabled. Most modules won't easily support it.
Enforce one-time initialisation of global module dict pointer with PEP-489.

Enforce one-time initialisation of global references whenever PEP-489 is enabled, not only when reloading is allowed, since we currently allow re-rerunning the initial setup part of the module init function.
Avoid "unused parameter" C warning if no builtins are being looked up.
Generalise initial "0" setting of constants which failed for memoryview slices. Remove the special case setup for memoryview slices and integrate it into the normal "default_value" scheme.

Split helper function for setting initial module attributes off the PEP-489 module create function, which will eventually be removed.
See #1923.

title: [WIP] gradually enable PEP-489 features
